<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-05-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-05-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="1095" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1095">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.11/4090.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Brazilian Minister at Mexico City</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-04">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 4, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>We are much pleased to learn of your successful efforts to secure train
                            for Americans desiring to leave Mexico; also gratified to know that
                            General Huerta has given assurance of protection so far as his forces
                            are concerned to foreigners returning to Tampico District for the care
                            of the oil wells. General Carranza has also promised protection where he
                            is in control.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">W. J. Bryan</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>